# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 79TH LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy welcomes
# its 79TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE — HACK (Facebook/Meta, 2013-present) —
# and its FIRST documented Hack tooling CLI mechanism: OCaml's stdlib
# `Arg` module (since Hack's type checker is OCaml-implemented while
# the user-facing language is Hack).
# Taxonomy now spans 324 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 79 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R582 Rust=53 env_logger/trail → R583 Go=53
# zerolog/SecretScanner → R584 TS-Node=53 pino/release) followed by 1
# NEW LANGUAGE (R585 Hack THIS).  Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=53,
# Go=53, TypeScript-Node=53 (three-way tie at 53 since R584).
#
# Hack is DISTINCT from every other documented language by being:
#   1. A STRICT-TYPED PHP DERIVATIVE — PHP source files start with
#      `<?hh` (Hack header) instead of `<?php`; same SYNTAX BASIS
#      (curly braces, dollar-sign variables, arrow operator) but
#      ADDITIONAL TYPE SYSTEM + async/await + collections + XHP
#   2. AN INDUSTRIAL-SCALE TYPED MIGRATION OF A DYNAMIC LANGUAGE —
#      Facebook migrated tens of millions of lines of PHP code to
#      Hack from 2013-2018, gradually adding strict-mode type
#      annotations.  Comparable in scale to Twitter's Scala
#      migration or Microsoft's TypeScript adoption
#   3. RUNTIME-ENFORCED + TYPECHECKER-VERIFIED — Hack code runs on
#      HHVM which enforces SOME type checks at runtime (parameter
#      checks, return value checks); the static type checker
#      (`hh_client check`) catches ADDITIONAL type errors that
#      the runtime wouldn't detect.  Dual-layer typing.
#   4. ASYNC-AWAIT WITHOUT A SCHEDULER VM PRIMITIVE — Hack's
#      `async function`/`await $promise` syntax compiles to
#      CONTINUATIONS the HHVM scheduler interleaves.  Influenced
#      by F# async workflows; predates Rust async by years
#   5. XHP — XML-like syntax in PHP for HTML templating with
#      strict type-checked component attributes; influenced
#      React's JSX (Facebook engineers transferred XHP design
#      ideas when building React)
#
# The taxonomy now documents the PHP → Hack lineage where Hack
# represents the typed-strict evolution path.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS HACK AND WHY IS IT THE 79TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Hack is Facebook's typed PHP dialect.  Distinguishing features:
#
#   1. <?hh HEADER + GRADUAL TYPING — Hack files start with `<?hh`
#      instead of `<?php`.  Within Hack files, code can mix typed
#      and untyped sections; the type checker reports errors
#      for type-annotated functions only by default.  `<?hh //
#      strict` mode requires ALL functions to be typed:
#
#          <?hh // strict
#
#          function greet(string $name): string {
#              return "Hello, " . $name;
#          }
#
#          function add(int $a, int $b): int {
#              return $a + $b;
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * PHP: dynamic typing with optional declare(strict_types=1)
#         * TypeScript: opt-in typing on top of JavaScript
#         * Hack: strict typing as primary mode + gradual variant
#
#   2. ASYNC/AWAIT VIA CONTINUATIONS — Hack added async/await in
#      2014 (before C# 5.0's async was common in PHP):
#
#          <?hh // strict
#          async function fetch_user(int $id): Awaitable<User> {
#              $row = await SQLQuery::genRow(
#                  "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?", $id);
#              return new User($row);
#          }
#
#          async function fetch_two_users(int $a, int $b): Awaitable<vec<User>> {
#              concurrent {
#                  $user_a = await fetch_user($a);
#                  $user_b = await fetch_user($b);
#              }
#              return vec[$user_a, $user_b];
#          }
#
#      Async code compiles to CONTINUATIONS that HHVM's scheduler
#      interleaves.  `concurrent { ... }` block allows multiple
#      `await` calls to run in parallel.
#
#   3. COLLECTIONS WITH LITERAL SYNTAX — Hack added typed
#      collection literals distinct from PHP's polymorphic array:
#
#          $vec = vec[1, 2, 3];           // ordered list
#          $dict = dict['a' => 1, 'b' => 2];  // string-keyed map
#          $keyset = keyset['a', 'b'];    // unique-string set
#          $map = Map { 'a' => 1, 'b' => 2 };  // mutable Map
#          $imm_map = ImmMap { 'a' => 1 };     // immutable Map
#
#      Each collection has STRICT TYPE PARAMETERS (vec<int>,
#      dict<string, int>) checked at static-analysis time.
#      PHP's `array()` is still available but the type checker
#      encourages migration to typed collections.
#
#   4. XHP FOR HTML TEMPLATING — Hack includes XHP: XML-like
#      syntax for HTML templating with type-checked attributes:
#
#          <?hh // strict
#
#          class :ui:button extends :x:element {
#              attribute string href @required;
#              attribute string label @required;
#              attribute string color = 'blue';
#              children empty;
#
#              protected function render(): XHPRoot {
#                  return <a href={$this->:href}
#                            class={"button-".$this->:color}>
#                      {$this->:label}
#                  </a>;
#              }
#          }
#
#          // Use:
#          $btn = <ui:button href="/click" label="Click me!" />;
#          echo $btn->toString();
#
#      XHP directly influenced REACT'S JSX SYNTAX — Facebook
#      engineers transferred XHP design ideas when building
#      React.  FIRST documented language in the taxonomy whose
#      template syntax directly inspired JSX.
#
#   5. PIPE OPERATOR — Hack's `|>` pipe operator chains
#      function calls with `$$` as the placeholder for the
#      left-hand value:
#
#          $result = $input
#              |> trim($$)
#              |> strtolower($$)
#              |> Vec\filter($$, $x ==> $x !== '');
#
#      Influenced JavaScript's pipeline-operator proposal (TC39
#      Stage 2) + Elixir's `|>` adoption + R's `%>%`/`|>`.
#
#   6. HHVM RUNTIME — Hack runs on HHVM (HipHop Virtual Machine),
#      Facebook's high-performance PHP JIT compiler.  HHVM:
#         * Compiles PHP/Hack to bytecode then JIT-compiles to
#           machine code
#         * Achieves 5-10x speedups over PHP-CLI for typical
#           Hack code
#         * Runs on Linux + macOS (BSD-style)
#         * Includes async runtime for Hack's async/await
#         * Includes Hack's collection types as built-in C++ ops
#      Compare:
#         * PHP: official PHP-CLI / Apache mod_php / php-fpm
#         * Hack: HHVM only (HHVM dropped pure PHP support in
#                 2018 to focus on Hack)
#
# Use cases for Hack:
#   * Facebook/Meta's primary server-side language (tens of
#     millions of LoC in Hack)
#   * Slack's earlier backend (migrated from Hack to Java in
#     2020 but Hack was their original choice)
#   * Box.com backend
#   * Various enterprise PHP shops migrating to strict typing
#   * WordPress Calypso (Automattic's React+Hack admin UI)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE hh_client CLI — OCaml stdlib Arg.parse + triple-tuple options
#
# hh_client is written in OCaml.  Argv parsing is in
# hphp/hack/src/client/clientArgs.ml using OCaml stdlib
# `Arg.parse`:
#
#     open Hh_prelude
#
#     let parse_check_args cmd ~from_default : ClientEnv.client_check_env =
#         let autostart = ref true in
#         let config = ref [] in
#         let mode = ref None in
#         (* ... ~50 more refs for each option ... *)
#
#         let usage = Printf.sprintf
#             "Usage: %s [COMMAND] [OPTION]... [WWW-ROOT]\n\n
#              Valid values for COMMAND:\n
#              \tcheck\t\tShows current Hack errors\n
#              \tstart\t\tStarts a Hack server\n
#              \tstop\t\tStops a Hack server\n
#              \trestart\t\tRestarts a Hack server\n
#              \tlsp\t\tRuns a persistent language service\n
#              \trage\t\tReport a bug\n"
#             Sys.argv.(0) in
#
#         let options = [
#             ("--allow-non-opt-build", Arg.Set allow_non_opt_build, " ...");
#             ("--autostart-server", Arg.Bool (fun b -> autostart := b), " ...");
#             ("--config", Arg.String (fun s -> config := s :: !config), " ...");
#             ("--from", Arg.String (fun s -> from := s), " ...");
#             ("--ignore-hh-version", Arg.Set ignore_hh_version, " ...");
#             ("--lsp", Arg.Unit (fun () -> set_mode MODE_LSP), " ...");
#             ("--json", Arg.Set output_json, " ...");
#             ("--max-errors", Arg.Int (fun n -> max_errors := Some n), " ...");
#             ("--mini-state", Arg.String (fun s -> mini_state := Some s), " ...");
#             ("--no-load", Arg.Set no_load, " ...");
#             ("--retries", Arg.Int (fun n -> timeout := Some n), " ...");
#             ("--save-state", Arg.String (fun s -> save_state := s), " ...");
#             ("--timeout", Arg.Float (fun f -> timeout := Some f), " ...");
#             ("--version", Arg.Set version, " ...");
#             (* ... hundreds more options ... *)
#         ] in
#
#         Arg.parse (Arg.align options) (fun x -> args := x :: !args) usage;
#         (* ... build ClientEnv from refs ... *)
#
# OCaml stdlib `Arg` distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. TRIPLE-TUPLE OPTION SPEC — Each option is a 3-tuple:
#      `(flag_name, spec, doc_string)`.  `spec` is a SUM TYPE
#      (OCaml variant) with constructors for each supported
#      flag type:
#         Arg.Unit (unit -> unit)     — no-arg flag
#         Arg.Bool (bool -> unit)     — boolean arg flag
#         Arg.Set (bool ref)          — set ref to true
#         Arg.Clear (bool ref)        — set ref to false
#         Arg.String (string -> unit) — string arg flag
#         Arg.Set_string (string ref) — set string ref
#         Arg.Int (int -> unit)       — integer arg flag
#         Arg.Set_int (int ref)       — set int ref
#         Arg.Float (float -> unit)   — float arg flag
#         Arg.Set_float (float ref)   — set float ref
#         Arg.Tuple [spec; spec; ...] — multi-arg compound flag
#         Arg.Symbol [vals] (string -> unit) — enum arg
#         Arg.Rest (string -> unit)   — catch-all remaining args
#         Arg.Expand (string -> string array) — recursive expansion
#
#      Each spec type is a function taking the parsed value
#      (where the flag has an arg) or unit (for switch flags).
#      FIRST documented argv parser with SUM-TYPE spec constructor
#      pattern.
#
#   2. Arg.align FOR HELP TEXT ALIGNMENT — Helper that takes
#      the option list and aligns the documentation column so
#      that all `--flag-name <ARG>` portions are padded to the
#      same width before the doc text:
#
#          Without Arg.align:
#              --foo <arg>  Documentation for foo
#              --bar  Documentation for bar
#              --baz <arg>  Documentation for baz
#
#          With Arg.align:
#              --foo <arg>  Documentation for foo
#              --bar        Documentation for bar
#              --baz <arg>  Documentation for baz
#
#      Compare:
#         * GNU getopt_long: no alignment helper
#         * clap: alignment built into formatter
#         * Python argparse: alignment via formatter classes
#         * OCaml Arg: Arg.align as separate helper function
#      FIRST documented argv parser with explicit standalone
#      alignment helper.
#
#   3. ANON_FUN FOR POSITIONAL ARGS — Positional arguments
#      (not matching any flag) are passed to a SECOND
#      callback function:
#
#          Arg.parse options anon_fun usage
#                                ^^^^^^^^
#          where anon_fun: string -> unit
#
#      Each positional arg invokes anon_fun.  Compare:
#         * Most argv parsers: positionals collected in array
#         * OCaml Arg: positionals delivered via callback function
#      FIRST documented argv parser with callback-style
#      positional-arg delivery.
#
#   4. OCAML-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — OCaml's Arg module is
#      THE standard CLI for OCaml binaries:
#         * dune (OCaml build system)
#         * ocamlc + ocamlopt + ocaml + ocamllex + menhir
#         * coq + rocq (theorem prover)
#         * unison (file synchronizer)
#         * mldonkey (P2P client)
#         * frama-c (C static analyzer)
#         * hh_client (Hack type checker — THIS)
#         * facebook/buck2 client
#         * GitHub Pinafore federated platforms
#         * The entire opam package ecosystem
#      Compare every other documented argv parser — none have
#      OCaml-ecosystem foundational provenance.  FIRST documented
#      argv parser tied to the OCaml standard library.
#
#   5. SIDE-EFFECT-DRIVEN PARSING — Each Arg.<Type> spec is
#      a function that mutates state via the calling
#      module's refs.  Parsing finishes when all argv elements
#      have been consumed; final state is read from the refs
#      after Arg.parse returns.  Compare:
#         * clap/structopt: parsing yields a structured value
#         * yargs/commander: builder yields parsed object
#         * OCaml Arg: parsing has SIDE EFFECTS on refs;
#                       caller reads refs after parse returns
#      FIRST documented argv parser with explicit ref-mutation
#      semantics.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented argv parser:
#
#   1. SUM-TYPE SPEC CONSTRUCTOR PATTERN — OCaml's variant
#      types let Arg.spec be a SUM TYPE.  FIRST documented argv
#      parser using sum-type variants for option specifications.
#
#   2. SEPARATE ALIGNMENT HELPER — Most parsers have built-in
#      alignment.  OCaml Arg uses Arg.align as a separate
#      function applied to the option list before passing to
#      Arg.parse.
#
#   3. CALLBACK POSITIONAL-ARGS — Most parsers collect
#      positionals in arrays.  OCaml Arg delivers them via
#      a user-supplied anon_fun callback.
#
#   4. OCAML-STDLIB PROVENANCE — Every other documented argv
#      parser is third-party.  OCaml Arg is shipped with the
#      OCaml compiler since 1996.
#
#   5. SIDE-EFFECT-DRIVEN — Most modern parsers return parsed
#      results.  OCaml Arg parses by mutating refs in scope.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/facebook/hhvm/blob/master/hphp/hack/src/client/clientArgs.ml
# `parse_check_args` function + usage string for COMMAND list.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _hh_cmds
_hh_cmds=(
    'check:show current Hack type errors (default)'
    'start:start a Hack type-check server'
    'stop:stop the Hack server'
    'restart:restart the Hack server'
    'lsp:run a persistent language service (LSP)'
    'rage:report a bug (capture diagnostic info)'
    'saved-state-project-metadata:output project metadata for current saved state'
    'download-saved-state:download a Hack saved state'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '--version[print Hack/HHVM version]' \
    '--autostart-server=[automatically start server if not running]:bool:(true false)' \
    '--config=[set a server config option (key=value)]:config:' \
    '--from=[client identifier (vim/emacs/[sh])]:from:(vim emacs sublime nuclide [sh])' \
    '--ignore-hh-version[ignore HHVM version mismatch with server]' \
    '--json[output errors as JSON]' \
    '--jsonl[output errors as JSONL (one per line)]' \
    '--max-errors=[limit number of errors reported]:N:' \
    '--mini-state=[path to mini state file]:file:_files' \
    '--no-load[do not load saved state]' \
    '--retries=[number of times to retry server connection]:N:' \
    '--save-state=[save server state to file]:file:_files' \
    '--save-64bit=[save 64-bit naming table to file]:file:_files' \
    '--saved-state-ignore-hhconfig[ignore .hhconfig when loading saved state]' \
    '--show-spinner=[show spinner during long operations]:bool:(true false)' \
    '--stdin-name=[treat stdin as having this filename]:filename:' \
    '--timeout=[timeout in seconds for connecting to server]:N:' \
    '--watchman-debug-logging[enable watchman debug logging]' \
    '--allow-non-opt-build[allow client to talk to non-optimized server build]' \
    '--logname[print log file location and exit]' \
    '--monitor-logname[print monitor log location and exit]' \
    '--client-logname[print client log location and exit]' \
    '--lsp-logname[print LSP log location and exit]' \
    '--lock-file[print server lock file location and exit]' \
    '--prechecked=[enable prechecked dependencies]:bool:(true false)' \
    '--sort-results[sort error results alphabetically]' \
    '--show-tast[show TAST (typed AST) for verified file]' \
    '--ide-logname[print IDE service log location and exit]' \
    '--output-json[alias for --json]' \
    '--output-jsonl[alias for --jsonl]' \
    '--rename-before=[rename a symbol (before name)]:name:' \
    '*--warning-switch=[enable/disable a warning by code]:switch:' \
    '*--invalid-warning-code=[suppress invalid warning code]:code:' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'hh_client subcommand' _hh_cmds
        _files -/
        ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        _files
        ret=0
        ;;
esac

return ret
